# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sciter-ui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:sciter-ui/cascading-style-sheets] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:sciter-ui/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] A **graphics library** or **graphics API** is a program library designed to aid in rendering computer graphics to a monitor.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] This typically involves providing optimized versions of functions that handle common rendering tasks.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] This can be done purely in software and running on the CPU, common in embedded systems, or being hardware accelerated by a GPU, more common in PCs.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] By employing these functions, a program can assemble an image to be output to a monitor.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] This relieves the programmer of the task of creating and optimizing these functions, and allows them to focus on building the graphics program.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Graphics libraries are mainly used in video games and simulations.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] The use of graphics libraries in connection with video production systems, such as Pixar RenderMan, is not covered here.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Some APIs use Graphics Library (GL) in their name, notably OpenGL and WebGL.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Dedicated graphics processors use RAM allocated directly to the graphics processor rather than the computer’s main system memory.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] This RAM is usually specifically selected with the expected sequential load of the graphics card in mind (see GDDR).
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Sometimes systems with dedicated discrete graphics processors were called “DIS” systems in contrast to “UMA” systems.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Technologies such as 3dfx's Scan-Line Interleave, Nvidia's SLI and NVLink, and AMD's CrossFire allow multiple graphics processors to simultaneously display images on one screen, increasing the computational power available for graphics processing.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] However, these technologies are becoming increasingly rare; most games do not utilize all the capabilities of multiple graphics processors since most users cannot afford them.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Today, laptops and mini-PCs require powerful integrated graphics.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] In many cases, quality integrated graphics can replace a discrete graphics card, enhancing laptop portability and mini-PC compactness while maintaining performance.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Integrated graphics processors (IGPU), integrated graphics, shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architectures (UMA) use part of the computer’s RAM rather than dedicated graphics memory.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] IGP may be integrated into the motherboard as part of its northbridge chipset or on a single chip (integrated circuit) with the central processor (e.g., AMD APU or Intel HD Graphics).
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] On some motherboards, AMD’s IGP may use sideport dedicated memory: a separate fixed block of high-performance memory allocated for use by the graphics processor.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] As of early 2007, computers with integrated graphics accounted for about 90% of all PC shipments.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] They are less expensive to implement than dedicated graphics processing but generally less powerful.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Historically, integrated processing was considered unsuitable for 3D games or graphics-intensive applications but could run less resource-demanding programs like Adobe Flash.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] Examples of such IGPs include offerings from SiS and VIA around 2004.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] However, modern integrated graphics processors such as AMD Accelerated Processing Unit and Intel Graphics Technology (HD, UHD, Iris, Iris Pro, Iris Plus, and Xe-LP) can handle 2D graphics or undemanding 3D graphics.
[src:sciter-ui/graphics-library] In systems with a “unified memory architecture” (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, PS5, and Xbox Series (among others), the CPU cores and GPU unit share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Web browsers receive HTML documents from a web server or from local storage and render the documents into multimedia web pages.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML describes the structure of a web page semantically and originally included cues for its appearance.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages.
[src:sciter-ui/html] With HTML constructs, images and other objects such as interactive forms may be embedded into the rendered page.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML provides a means to create structured documents by denoting structural semantics for text such as headings, paragraphs, lists, links, quotes, and other items.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML elements are delineated by *tags*, written using angle brackets.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Tags such as `<img>` and `<input>` directly introduce content into the page.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Other tags such as `<p>` and its corresponding closing tag `</p>` surround and provide information about document text and may include sub-element tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Browsers do not display the HTML tags, but use them to interpret the content of the page.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML can embed programs written in a scripting language such as JavaScript, which affects the behavior and content of web pages.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The inclusion of CSS defines the look and layout of content.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), former maintainer of the HTML and current maintainer of the CSS standards, has encouraged the use of CSS over explicit presentational HTML since 1997.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A form of HTML, known as HTML5, is used to display video and audio, primarily using the `<canvas>` element, together with JavaScript.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In 1980, the physicist Tim Berners-Lee, a contractor at CERN, proposed and prototyped ENQUIRE, a system for CERN researchers to use and share documents.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In 1989, Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Berners-Lee specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:sciter-ui/html] That year, Berners-Lee and CERN data systems engineer Robert Cailliau collaborated on a joint request for funding, but the project was not formally adopted by CERN.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In his personal notes of 1990, Berners-Lee listed "some of the many areas in which hypertext is used"; an encyclopedia is the first entry.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Tim Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:sciter-ui/html] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by CERN SGML, an in-house Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML)-based documentation format at CERN.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML is a markup language that web browsers use to interpret and compose text, images, and other material into visible or audible web pages.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Default characteristics for every item of HTML markup are defined in the browser, and these characteristics can be altered or enhanced by the web page designer's additional use of CSS.
[src:sciter-ui/html] These formatting commands were derived from the commands used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:sciter-ui/html] However, the SGML concept of generalized markup is based on elements (nested annotated ranges with attributes) rather than merely print effects, with separate structure and markup.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML has been progressively moved in this direction with CSS.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The draft expired after six months, but was notable for its acknowledgment of the NCSA Mosaic browser's custom tag for embedding in-line images, reflecting the IETF's philosophy of basing standards on successful prototypes.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Similarly, Dave Raggett's competing Internet Draft, "HTML+ (Hypertext Markup Format)", from late 1993, suggested standardizing already-implemented features like tables and fill-out forms.
[src:sciter-ui/html] After the HTML and HTML+ drafts expired in early 1994, the IETF created an HTML Working Group.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In 1995, this working group completed "HTML 2.0", the first HTML specification intended to be treated as a standard against which future implementations should be based.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Further development under the auspices of the IETF was stalled by competing interests.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Since 1996, the HTML specifications have been maintained, with input from commercial software vendors, by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:sciter-ui/html] In 2000, HTML became an international standard (ISO/IEC 15445:2000).
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML 4.01 was published in late 1999, with further errata published through 2001.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In 2004, development began on HTML5 in the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG), which became a joint deliverable with the W3C in 2008, and was completed and standardized on 28 October 2014.
[src:sciter-ui/html] It was the first version developed and standardized exclusively by the W3C, as the IETF had closed its HTML Working Group on 12 September 1996.
[src:sciter-ui/html] were omitted due to a mutual agreement between the two companies.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML 4 is an SGML application conforming to ISO 8879 – SGML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] was reissued with minor edits without incrementing the version number.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML", based on HTML 4.01 Strict) was published as an ISO/IEC international standard.
[src:sciter-ui/html] (ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1, Subcommittee 34 – Document description and processing languages).
[src:sciter-ui/html] After HTML 4.01, there were no new versions of HTML for many years, as the development of the parallel, XML-based language XHTML occupied the W3C's HTML Working Group.
[src:sciter-ui/html] an informal CERN document listing 18 HTML tags, was first mentioned in public.
[src:sciter-ui/html] IIIR Working Group as an Internet Draft (a rough proposal for a standard).
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML+ was published by the IETF as an Internet Draft and was a competing proposal to the Hypertext Markup Language draft.
[src:sciter-ui/html] It included many of the capabilities that were in Raggett's HTML+ proposal, such as support for tables, text flow around figures, and the display of complex mathematical formulas.
[src:sciter-ui/html] but HTML 3.0 did not succeed for several reasons.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The draft was considered very large at 150 pages and the pace of browser development, as well as the number of interested parties, had outstripped the resources of the IETF.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Browser vendors, including Microsoft and Netscape at the time, chose to implement different subsets of HTML 3's draft features as well as to introduce their own extensions to it.
[src:sciter-ui/html] has abandoned any attempt to be an SGML application and has explicitly defined its own "html" serialization, in addition to an alternative XML-based XHTML5 serialization.
[src:sciter-ui/html] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its HTML Working Group with clear milestones for HTML5.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The W3C developed a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which was the target date for recommendation.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In January 2011, the WHATWG renamed its "HTML5" living standard to "HTML".
[src:sciter-ui/html] The W3C nevertheless continued its project to release HTML5.
[src:sciter-ui/html] W3C will continue the HTML5 specification work, focusing on a single definitive standard, which is considered a "snapshot" by WHATWG.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The WHATWG organization will continue its work with HTML5 as a "Living Standard".
[src:sciter-ui/html] The concept of a living standard is that it is never complete and is always being updated and improved.
[src:sciter-ui/html] New features can be added but functionality will not be removed.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In December 2012, W3C designated HTML5 as a Candidate Recommendation.
[src:sciter-ui/html] is "two 100% complete and fully interoperable implementations".
[src:sciter-ui/html] In September 2014, W3C moved HTML5 to Proposed Recommendation.
[src:sciter-ui/html] meaning the specification process is complete.
[src:sciter-ui/html] XHTML is a separate language that began as a reformulation of HTML 4.01 using XML 1.0.
[src:sciter-ui/html] It is now referred to as *the XML syntax for HTML* and is no longer being developed as a separate standard.
[src:sciter-ui/html] On 28 May 2019, the W3C announced that WHATWG would be the sole publisher of the HTML and DOM standards.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The W3C and WHATWG had been publishing competing standards since 2012.
[src:sciter-ui/html] While the W3C standard was identical to the WHATWG in 2007 the standards have since progressively diverged due to different design decisions.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The WHATWG "Living Standard" had been the *de facto* web standard for some time.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The W3C periodically reviews and publishes snapshots of the WHATWG HTML specification as W3C Recommendations.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML markup consists of several key components, including those called *tags* (and their *attributes*), character-based *data types*, *character references* and *entity references*.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML tags most commonly come in pairs like `<h1>` and `</h1>`, although some represent *empty elements* and so are unpaired, for example `<img>`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The first tag in such a pair is the *start tag*, and the second is the *end tag* (they are also called *opening tags* and *closing tags*).
[src:sciter-ui/html] Another important component is the HTML *document type declaration*, which triggers standards mode rendering.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The text between `<html>` and `</html>` describes the web page, and the text between `<body>` and `</body>` is the visible page content.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The markup text `<title>This is a title</title>` defines the browser page title shown on browser tabs and window titles and the tag `<div>` defines a division of the page used for easy styling.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Between `<head>` and `</head>`, a `<meta>` element can be used to define webpage metadata.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The Document Type Declaration `<!DOCTYPE html>` is for HTML5.
[src:sciter-ui/html] If a declaration is not included, various browsers will revert to "quirks mode" for rendering.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML documents imply a structure of nested HTML elements.
[src:sciter-ui/html] These are indicated in the document by HTML *tags*, enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In the simple, general case, the extent of an element is indicated by a pair of tags: a "start tag" `<p>` and "end tag" `</p>`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The text content of the element, if any, is placed between these tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Tags may also enclose further tag markup between the start and end, including a mixture of tags and text.
[src:sciter-ui/html] This indicates further (nested) elements, as children of the parent element.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The start tag may also include the element's *attributes* within the tag.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Some elements, such as the line break `<br>` do not permit *any* embedded content, either text or further tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] These require only a single empty tag (akin to a start tag) and do not use an end tag.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Many tags, particularly the closing end tag for the very commonly used paragraph element `<p>`, are optional.
[src:sciter-ui/html] An HTML browser or other agent can infer the closure for the end of an element from the context and the structural rules defined by the HTML standard.
[src:sciter-ui/html] These rules are complex and not widely understood by most HTML authors.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The general form of an HTML element is therefore: `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">''content''</tag>`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Some HTML elements are defined as *empty elements* and take the form `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Empty elements may enclose no content, for instance, the `<br>` tag or the inline `<img>` tag.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The name of an HTML element is the name used in the tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The end tag's name is preceded by a slash character `/`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] If a tag has no content, an end tag is not allowed.
[src:sciter-ui/html] If attributes are not mentioned, default values are used in each case.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Header of the HTML document: `<head>...</head>`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] CSS can substantially change the rendering.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The difference between `<br>` and `<p>` is that `<br>` breaks a line without altering the semantic structure of the page, whereas `<p>` sections the page into paragraphs.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The element `<br>` is an *empty element* in that, although it may have attributes, it can take no content and it must not have an end tag.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The `href` attribute holds the URL address of the link.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Comments can help in the understanding of the markup and do not display in the webpage.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Most of the attributes of an element are name–value pairs, separated by `=` and written within the start tag of an element after the element's name.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The value may be enclosed in single or double quotes, although values consisting of certain characters can be left unquoted in HTML (but not XHTML).
[src:sciter-ui/html] Leaving attribute values unquoted is considered unsafe.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In contrast with name-value pair attributes, there are some attributes that affect the element simply by their presence in the start tag of the element, like the `ismap` attribute for the `img` element.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Most elements take the language-related attribute `dir` to specify text direction, such as with "rtl" for right-to-left text in, for example, Arabic, Persian or Hebrew.
[src:sciter-ui/html] As of version 4.0, HTML defines a set of 252 character entity references and a set of 1,114,050 numeric character references, both of which allow individual characters to be written via simple markup, rather than literally.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A literal character and its markup counterpart are considered equivalent and are rendered identically.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The ability to "escape" characters in this way allows for the characters `<` and `&` (when written as `&lt;` and `&amp;`, respectively) to be interpreted as character data, rather than markup.
[src:sciter-ui/html] For example, a literal `<` normally indicates the start of a tag, and `&` normally indicates the start of a character entity reference or numeric character reference; writing it as `&amp;` or `&#x26;` or `&#38;` allows `&` to be included in the content of an element or in the value of an attribute.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The double-quote character (`"`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&quot;` or `&#x22;` or `&#34;` when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Equivalently, the single-quote character (`'`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&#x27;` or `&#39;` (or as `&apos;` in HTML5 or XHTML documents) when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:sciter-ui/html] If document authors overlook the need to escape such characters, some browsers can be very forgiving and try to use context to guess their intent.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The result is still invalid markup, which makes the document less accessible to other browsers and to other user agents that may try to parse the document for search and indexing purposes for example.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Escaping also allows for characters that are not easily typed, or that are not available in the document's character encoding, to be represented within the element and attribute content.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Unicode character encodings such as UTF-8 are compatible with all modern browsers and allow direct access to almost all the characters of the world's writing systems.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML defines several data types for element content, such as script data and stylesheet data, and a plethora of types for attribute values, including IDs, names, URIs, numbers, units of length, languages, media descriptors, colors, character encodings, dates and times, and so on.
[src:sciter-ui/html] All of these data types are specializations of character data.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML documents are required to start with a document type declaration (informally, a "doctype").
[src:sciter-ui/html] In browsers, the doctype helps to define the rendering mode—particularly whether to use quirks mode.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The original purpose of the doctype was to enable the parsing and validation of HTML documents by SGML tools based on the document type definition (DTD).
[src:sciter-ui/html] The DTD to which the DOCTYPE refers contains a machine-readable grammar specifying the permitted and prohibited content for a document conforming to such a DTD.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Browsers, on the other hand, do not implement HTML as an application of SGML and as consequence do not read the DTD.
[src:sciter-ui/html] This declaration references the DTD for the "strict" version of HTML 4.01.
[src:sciter-ui/html] SGML-based validators read the DTD in order to properly parse the document and to perform validation.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In modern browsers, a valid doctype activates standards mode as opposed to quirks mode.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In addition, HTML 4.01 provides Transitional and Frameset DTDs, as explained below.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The transitional type is the most inclusive, incorporating current tags as well as older or "deprecated" tags, with the Strict DTD excluding deprecated tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The frameset has all tags necessary to make frames on a page along with the tags included in transitional type.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Semantic HTML is a way of writing HTML that emphasizes the meaning of the encoded information over its presentation (look).
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML has included semantic markup from its inception, but has also included presentational markup, such as `<font>`, `<i>`, and `<center>` tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] There are also the semantically neutral div and span tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Since the late 1990s, when Cascading Style Sheets were beginning to work in most browsers, web authors have been encouraged to avoid the use of presentational HTML markup with a view to the separation of content and presentation.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In a 2001 discussion of the Semantic Web, Tim Berners-Lee and others gave examples of ways in which intelligent software "agents" may one day automatically crawl the web and find, filter, and correlate previously unrelated, published facts for the benefit of human users.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Such agents are not commonplace even now, but some of the ideas of Web 2.0, mashups and price comparison websites may be coming close.
[src:sciter-ui/html] An important type of web agent that does crawl and read web pages automatically, without prior knowledge of what it might find, is the web crawler or search-engine spider.
[src:sciter-ui/html] These software agents are dependent on the semantic clarity of web pages they find as they use various techniques and algorithms to read and index millions of web pages a day and provide web users with search facilities without which the World Wide Web's usefulness would be greatly reduced.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Presentational markup tags are deprecated in current HTML and XHTML recommendations.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The majority of presentational features from previous versions of HTML are no longer allowed as they lead to poorer accessibility, higher cost of site maintenance, and larger document sizes.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Good semantic HTML also improves the accessibility of web documents (see also Web Content Accessibility Guidelines).
[src:sciter-ui/html] For example, when a screen reader or audio browser can correctly ascertain the structure of a document, it will not waste the visually impaired user's time by reading out repeated or irrelevant information when it has been marked up correctly.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML documents can be delivered by the same means as any other computer file.
[src:sciter-ui/html] However, they are most often delivered either by HTTP from a web server or by email.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The World Wide Web is composed primarily of HTML documents transmitted from web servers to web browsers using the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:sciter-ui/html] However, HTTP is used to serve images, sound, and other content, in addition to HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] To allow the web browser to know how to handle each document it receives, other information is transmitted along with the document.
[src:sciter-ui/html] This meta data usually includes the MIME type (e.g., text/html or application/xhtml+xml) and the character encoding (see Character encodings in HTML).
[src:sciter-ui/html] In modern browsers, the MIME type that is sent with the HTML document may affect how the document is initially interpreted.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A document sent with the XHTML MIME type is expected to be well-formed XML; syntax errors may cause the browser to fail to render it.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The same document sent with the HTML MIME type might be displayed successfully since some browsers are more lenient with HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The W3C recommendations state that XHTML 1.0 documents that follow guidelines set forth in the recommendation's Appendix C may be labeled with either MIME Type.
[src:sciter-ui/html] XHTML 1.1 also states that XHTML 1.1 documents should be labeled with either MIME type.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Most graphical email clients allow the use of a subset of HTML (often ill-defined) to provide formatting and semantic markup not available with plain text.
[src:sciter-ui/html] This may include typographic information like colored headings, emphasized and quoted text, inline images and diagrams.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Many such clients include both a GUI editor for composing HTML e-mail messages and a rendering engine for displaying them.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Use of HTML in e-mail is criticized by some because of compatibility issues, because it can help disguise phishing attacks, because of accessibility issues for blind or visually impaired people, because it can confuse spam filters and because the message size is larger than plain text.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The most common filename extension for files containing HTML is .html.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A common abbreviation of this is .htm, which originated because some operating systems limit file extensions to three letters.
[src:sciter-ui/html] An HTML Application (HTA; file extension .hta) is a Microsoft Windows application that uses HTML and Dynamic HTML in a browser to provide the application's graphical interface.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A regular HTML file is confined to the security model of the web browser's security, communicating only to web servers and manipulating only web page objects and site cookies.
[src:sciter-ui/html] An HTA runs as a fully trusted application and therefore has more privileges, like creation/editing/removal of files and Windows Registry entries.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Because they operate outside the browser's security model, HTAs cannot be executed via HTTP, but must be downloaded (just like an EXE file) and executed from local file system.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Since its inception, HTML and its associated protocols gained acceptance relatively quickly.
[src:sciter-ui/html] However, no clear standards existed in the early years of the language.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Though its creators originally conceived of HTML as a semantic language devoid of presentation details, practical uses pushed many presentational elements and attributes into the language, driven largely by the various browser vendors.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The latest standards surrounding HTML reflect efforts to overcome the sometimes chaotic development of the language and to create a rational foundation for building both meaningful and well-presented documents.
[src:sciter-ui/html] To return HTML to its role as a semantic language, the W3C has developed style languages such as CSS and XSL to shoulder the burden of presentation.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In conjunction, the HTML specification has slowly reined in the presentational elements.
[src:sciter-ui/html] There are two axes differentiating various variations of HTML as currently specified: SGML-based HTML versus XML-based HTML (referred to as XHTML) on one axis, and strict versus transitional (loose) versus frameset on the other axis.
[src:sciter-ui/html] One difference in the latest HTML specifications lies in the distinction between the SGML-based specification and the XML-based specification.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The XML-based specification is usually called XHTML to distinguish it clearly from the more traditional definition.
[src:sciter-ui/html] However, the root element name continues to be "html" even in the XHTML-specified HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The W3C intended XHTML 1.0 to be identical to HTML 4.01 except where limitations of XML over the more complex SGML require workarounds.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Because XHTML and HTML are closely related, they are sometimes documented in parallel.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In such circumstances, some authors conflate the two names as (X)HTML or X(HTML).
[src:sciter-ui/html] Like HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0 has three sub-specifications: strict, transitional, and frameset.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Aside from the different opening declarations for a document, the differences between an HTML 4.01 and XHTML 1.0 document—in each of the corresponding DTDs—are largely syntactic.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The underlying syntax of HTML allows many shortcuts that XHTML does not, such as elements with optional opening or closing tags, and even empty elements which must not have an end tag.
[src:sciter-ui/html] By contrast, XHTML requires all elements to have an opening tag and a closing tag.
[src:sciter-ui/html] XHTML, however, also introduces a new shortcut: an XHTML tag may be opened and closed within the same tag, by including a slash before the end of the tag like this: `<br/>`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The introduction of this shorthand, which is not used in the SGML declaration for HTML 4.01, may confuse earlier software unfamiliar with this new convention.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A fix for this is remove the slash preceding the closing angle bracket, as such: `<br>`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] To understand the subtle differences between HTML and XHTML, consider the transformation of a valid and well-formed XHTML 1.0 document that adheres to Appendix C (see below) into a valid HTML 4.01 document.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Change the document type declaration from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Ensure that the document's MIME type is set to `text/html`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] For both HTML and XHTML, this comes from the HTTP `Content-Type` header sent by the server.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Change the XML empty-element syntax to an HTML style empty element (`<br/>` to `<br>`).
[src:sciter-ui/html] Those are the main changes necessary to translate a document from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:sciter-ui/html] To translate from HTML to XHTML would also require the addition of any omitted opening or closing tags.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Whether coding in HTML or XHTML it may just be best to always include the optional tags within an HTML document rather than remembering which tags can be omitted.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A well-formed XHTML document adheres to all the syntax requirements of XML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] A valid document adheres to the content specification for XHTML, which describes the document structure.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The W3C recommends several conventions to ensure an easy migration between HTML and XHTML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] By carefully following the W3C's compatibility guidelines, a user agent should be able to interpret the document equally as HTML or XHTML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] For documents that are XHTML 1.0 and have been made compatible in this way, the W3C permits them to be served either as HTML (with a `text/html` MIME type), or as XHTML (with an `application/xhtml+xml` or `application/xml` MIME type).
[src:sciter-ui/html] When delivered as XHTML, browsers should use an XML parser, which adheres strictly to the XML specifications for parsing the document's contents.
[src:sciter-ui/html] HTML 4 defined three different versions of the language: Strict, Transitional (once called Loose), and Frameset.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The Strict version is intended for new documents and is considered best practice, while the Transitional and Frameset versions were developed to make it easier to transition documents that conformed to older HTML specifications or did not conform to any specification to a version of HTML 4.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The Transitional and Frameset versions allow for presentational markup, which is omitted in the Strict version.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Instead, cascading style sheets are encouraged to improve the presentation of HTML documents.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Because XHTML 1 only defines an XML syntax for the language defined by HTML 4, the same differences apply to XHTML 1 as well.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The Frameset version includes everything in the Transitional version, as well as the `frameset` element (used instead of `body`) and the `frame` element.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In addition to the above transitional differences, the frameset specifications (whether XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01) specify a different content model, with `frameset` replacing `body`, that contains either `frame` elements, or optionally `noframes` with a `body`.
[src:sciter-ui/html] As this list demonstrates, the loose versions of the specification are maintained for legacy support.
[src:sciter-ui/html] However, contrary to popular misconceptions, the move to XHTML does not imply a removal of this legacy support.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Rather the X in XML stands for extensible and the W3C is modularizing the entire specification and opens it up to independent extensions.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The primary achievement in the move from XHTML 1.0 to XHTML 1.1 is the modularization of the entire specification.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The strict version of HTML is deployed in XHTML 1.1 through a set of modular extensions to the base XHTML 1.1 specification.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Likewise, someone looking for the loose (transitional) or frameset specifications will find similar extended XHTML 1.1 support (much of it is contained in the legacy or frame modules).
[src:sciter-ui/html] Modularization also allows for separate features to develop on their own timetable.
[src:sciter-ui/html] So for example, XHTML 1.1 will allow quicker migration to emerging XML standards such as MathML (a presentational and semantic math language based on XML) and XForms—a new highly advanced web-form technology to replace the existing HTML forms.
[src:sciter-ui/html] In summary, the HTML 4 specification primarily reined in all the various HTML implementations into a single clearly written specification based on SGML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] XHTML 1.0, ported this specification, as is, to the new XML-defined specification.
[src:sciter-ui/html] Next, XHTML 1.1 takes advantage of the extensible nature of XML and modularizes the whole specification.
[src:sciter-ui/html] XHTML 2.0 was intended to be the first step in adding new features to the specification in a standards-body-based approach.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The HTML Living Standard, which is developed by WHATWG, is the official version, while W3C HTML5 is no longer separate from WHATWG.
[src:sciter-ui/html] WYSIWYG editors (*what you see is what you get*), are HTML editors in which the user lays out everything as it is to appear in the HTML document using a graphical user interface (GUI), such as Microsoft FrontPage, often similar to word processors.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The editor renders the document rather than showing the code, so authors do not require extensive knowledge of HTML.
[src:sciter-ui/html] The WYSIWYG editing model has been criticized, primarily because of the low quality of the generated code; there are various developers advocating a change to the WYSIWYM model (*what you see is what you mean*).
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:sciter-ui/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:sciter-ui/webview] A **WebView** is a web browser that is embedded within an app.
[src:sciter-ui/webview] Thus, a WebView is a large-scale software component that enables the use of web content within apps.
[src:sciter-ui/webview] In some cases, the entire functionality of the app is implemented this way.
[src:sciter-ui/webview] Other examples are Microsoft's legacy WebView, based on its deprecated EdgeHTML and MSHTML engines, and the WebView component in JavaFX.
